<text xml:lang="ta" type="edition">
  <body>
    <div rend="parallel">
      <lg xml:id="ITA100">
<l>mālē neṭiyōṉē kaṇṇaṉē viṇṇavarkku</l>
<l>mēlā viyaṉṟuḻāyk kaṇṇiyaṉē – mēlāy</l>
<l>viḷaviṉkāy kaṉṟiṉāl vīḻttavaṉē yeṉṟa</l>
<l>ṉaḷavaṉṟāl yāṉuṭaiya vaṉpu</l>
      </lg>
      <lg xml:lang="en">
<l>‘O Māl, Tall one, Kaṇṇaṉ, you above the celestials<note xml:lang="en" place="foot">The morphological difference in the two forms mēlā and mēlāy is that one is the vocative to the masculin form mēlaṉ while the second is marked for second person. It is not clear whether this is just poetic variation or whether there is a difference in semantic nuance.</note>,</l>
<l>you with the broad tulsi chaplet, you who brought down</l> 
<l>from above the fruits of the wood-apple tree with the calf,’ I said.</l>
<l>Without limit indeed is the love I have for you.</l>
      </lg>
    </div>
  </body>
</text>
